==English==

===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|abjuren}}, from {{der|en|la|abiūrō|t=deny upon oath}} (possibly via {{der|en|frm|abiurer|abjurer}}), formed from {{m|la|ab|t=from, away from}} + {{m|la|iūro|t=swear or take an oath}}, from {{m|la|iūs|t=law, right, duty}}.<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=3}}</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/æbˈdʒʊɹ/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-abjure.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ʊə(ɹ)|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|abjur}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} to [[renounce]] upon [[oath]]; to [[forswear]]; to [[disavow]]. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=5}}</ref>
#* '''1786''', {{w|William Beckford}}, ''Vathek; an Arabian Tale'':
#*: adore then the terrestrial influences, and '''abjure''' Mahomet.
#: {{ux|en|To '''abjure''' allegiance to a prince.}}
#: {{ux|en|To '''abjure''' the realm (''to swear to abandon it forever'').}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete|historical}} to cause one to renounce or recant. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{lb|en|transitive}} to [[reject]] with [[solemnity]]; to abandon [[forever]]; to [[repudiate]]; to [[disclaim]]. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: {{ux|en|To '''abjure''' errors.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1610|title=[[s:The Tempest|The Tempest]]|author={{w|William Shakespeare|Shakespeare}}|section=act 5 scene 1|passage=But this rough magic I here '''abjure''' [...]}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} to abstain from; to [[avoid]]; to [[shun]].

